[2] Ribeirão Preto, Sao Paulo state
Date: Wed 4 Jan 2017
Source: UOL Noticias [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://noticias.uol.com.br/ultimas-noticias/agencia-estado/2017/01/04/homem-morre-apos-contrair-febre-amarela-em-ribeirao-preto.htm


A man died after contracting yellow fever in Ribeirão Preto
-----------------------------------------------------------
A 52-year-old man died after contracting yellow fever in a rural area of Ribeirão Preto, in the interior of São Paulo state. According to the municipal Secretariat of Health, the patient went to the health network [facility] with symptoms of the disease and after 4 days was admitted and died on 26 Dec [2016]. The cause of death was confirmed on Tuesday, 3 [Jan 2017] by the Adolfo Lutz Institute.

This was the 2nd yellow fever death in the state in 2016. In April [2016], a 38-year-old man died of the disease in Bady Bassit, São José do Rio Preto [see ProMED-mail archive no. 20160509.4209766].

In these 2 cases, the patients were in forest areas having monkeys, possible hosts of the virus. The regions of Ribeirão Preto and Rio Preto had dead monkeys infected with yellow fever [virus] in 11 municipalities between July 2014 and December 2016. The [human] victims were not vaccinated against the disease. Preventive measures were taken in the 2 cities to prevent new occurrences.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[Cases of yellow fever (YF) were popping up in monkeys in various localities in Sao Paulo state last year (2016). Reports of dead monkeys indicate that there was sylvan (forest) yellow fever (YF) virus circulating in various localities in São Paulo state. Other than the 2 human cases cited above, there have been no other reported human cases.

Despite these YF infected monkeys indicating that sylvan (forest) transmission is occurring, the risk of spill-over into the human population is real. Timely immunization of humans in these areas is prudent and is an effective measure to prevent initiation of an urban transmission cycle with many human cases. The comments of Mod.RNA in 2 previous reports of the Sao Paulo state sylvan cases of yellow fever in 2016 are instructive.

A 1 Dec 2016 report posted in ProMED-PORT (in Portuguese) indicated that the dead monkeys were howlers, a species commonly involved in the sylvan cycle of YF virus transmission, and indicators of the presence of virus in the area. - Mod.TY]
